Bubble sort, insertion sort, and selection sort are all in-place sorting algorithms, meaning they don't require additional memory space to run and they sort the input data in-place. In the case of bubble sort and insertion sort, this means that the data is shifted left and right within the input array, while in the case of selection sort, the input array is iterated and the smallest value is selected and moved to the first position. All three algorithms are simple to implement and easy to understand but they have poor worst-case complexity, meaning they run in O(N^2) time.

Merge sort, quick sort, and heap sort are all external sorting algorithms, meaning they require additional memory space to run and they sort the input data in a separate sorted output array. In the case of merge sort, the input data is recursively sorted into smaller sub-arrays, which are then merged to produce the final sorted output. Quick sort is another well-known in-place sorting algorithm, but it has O(N log N) worst-case complexity, meaning it runs in linear time on sorted input data but can take exponential time on unsorted inputs. Heap sort, on the other hand, is a linear time sorting algorithm that works on a specially-designed data structure called a heap. It first builds a heap from the input data, then iterates through the heap and swaps adjacent elements to sort them in ascending order. Heap sort has O(N log N) worst-case complexity.

Below is a simple C++ code example for the heap sort algorithm:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <stdlib.h>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    int array[] = {1, 3, 5, 2};
    int size = sizeof(array) / sizeof(array[0]);

    heapify(array, size);
    sort(array, size);

    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        cout << array[i] << " ";
    }

    cout << endl;

    return 0;
}

void heapify(int array[], int size) {
    int max = array[0];
    int i = 0;

    for (; i < size / 2; i++) {
        int parent = i * 2;
        if (array[parent] > max) {
            max = array[parent];
            i = parent;
        }
    }

    for (i; i < size; i++) {
        array[i] = array[i + 1];
    }

    array[i] = max;
}

void sort(int array[], int size) {
    int i = 0;
    int j = 0;

    while (i < size / 2) {
        if (array[i] > array[j]) {
            int temp = array[i];
            array[i] = array[j];
            array[j] = temp;
            i++;
            j++;
        } else {
            i++;
        }
    }
}
```

Here, the `heapify` function builds a heap data structure from the input array, while the `sort` function iterates through the heap, swapping adjacent elements to sort them in ascending order. The code for `heapify` and `sort` are relatively simple and should be easy to modify to sort any other type of data.

